# Nowhere — Java Backend

## Build & Deploy

```
gradlew build
move file to home directory
gcloud run deploy
```

---

## Project Overview

Nowhere is a real-time collaborative storytelling game played over the web. Players collectively
build a world and then navigate it encounter-by-encounter, writing scenes, proposing actions, and
voting on outcomes together.

The backend is a **Spring Boot** service that manages game state, player sessions, text submissions,
and voting. It persists data to **Firebase/Firestore**, which both clients subscribe to for real-time
updates.

---

## Monorepo Structure

```
nowhere-storytelling-suite/
├── nowhere_java/           ← this backend (Spring Boot)
├── nowhere-game-client/    ← Angular app for the host/shared screen ("TV")
└── nowhere-player-client/  ← Angular app for individual players (phones)
```

The game-client is the shared display everyone watches. The player-client is each person's
individual device. Both receive real-time updates from Firestore.

---

## Key Packages

```
src/main/java/client/nowhere/
├── controller/     HTTP endpoints (game session, player session, collaborative text, etc.)
├── dao/            Firestore read/write helpers
├── factory/        Object construction (phases, outcomes, stories)
├── helper/         Core game logic (CollaborativeTextHelper, OutcomeTypeHelper, etc.)
├── model/          Domain objects (see below)
└── config/         Firebase config, CORS, etc.
```

---

## Core Domain Models

| Model | Description |
|---|---|
| `GameSession` | Top-level game; holds `GameState`, round number, player list, `AdventureMap`, `GameBoard` |
| `GameState` | Enum driving the full state machine (see Phase Reference below) |
| `ActiveGameStateSession` | Per-game server-side phase state; holds `TextSubmission[]` for the current phase |
| `ActivePlayerSession` | Per-player live state: `startTimer`, `contributionPhaseActive`, `writeTimerDone` |
| `AdventureMap` | Holds `EncounterLabel[]` — the named locations players create in world setup |
| `GameBoard` | `DungeonGrid`: a `Map<"x,y", Encounter>` representing the dungeon |
| `Encounter` | A single cell on the grid; links to a `Story` and an `EncounterLabel` |
| `Story` | A written scene: `prompt`, `authorId`, `selectedOptionId`, `Option[]`, `repercussions` |
| `Option` | A proposed action: `optionText`, `successText`, `OutcomeFork[]` |
| `TextSubmission` | A player's submission in a collaborative phase; has a `currentText` and `additions[]` |
| `OutcomeType` / `OutcomeTypeWithLabel` | Describes what a player is assigned to write about in a given phase |
| `Player` | A participant: `displayName`, `authorId`, `joinedAt`, `traits`, `playerCoordinates` |
| `Repercussion` / `RepercussionType` | Stat changes that result from story outcomes |
| `CollaborativeTextPhase` | Holds all `TextSubmission[]` for one phase keyed by `GameState` |
| `CollaborativePhaseTypeInstructions` | Per-phase writing config: `phaseModeInstructions`, `contributionPhaseInstructions`, `characterLimit` |

---

## Collaborative Writing Modes

Every collaborative writing phase runs in one of two modes:

**RAPID_FIRE** — Each player writes their own submission independently. Submissions are then ranked
by the number of additions other players made to them. Top N become the winners.

**SHARE_TEXT** — Players write an initial submission, then can add to each other's submissions
during a contribution phase. The game-client drives this with a two-ring nested timer: the outer
ring counts down the initial writing window; when it completes, the inner ring counts down the
contribution window.

---

## Game Flow (Dungeon Mode)

### Macro Structure

```
INIT → PREAMBLE
  │
  ▼
WORLD SETUP
  SET_ENCOUNTERS → SET_ENCOUNTERS_WINNERS          [RAPID_FIRE]
    EncounterLabels created on AdventureMap
  │
  ▼ (repeat for 2 rounds)
STORY WRITING (per round)
  WHAT_HAPPENS_HERE → WHAT_HAPPENS_HERE_WINNER     [SHARE_TEXT]
    Stories + Encounters placed on GameBoard
  WHAT_CAN_WE_TRY → WHAT_CAN_WE_TRY_WINNERS       [RAPID_FIRE]
    Options added to Stories
  HOW_DOES_THIS_RESOLVE → WINNERS                  [SHARE_TEXT]
    successText + OutcomeForks added to Options
  HOW_DOES_THIS_RESOLVE_AGAIN → WINNERS            [SHARE_TEXT]
  │
  ▼ (repeat per encounter in round)
ENCOUNTER RESOLUTION
  MAKE_CHOICE_VOTING → MAKE_CHOICE_WINNER
    story.selectedOptionId set by group vote
  MAKE_OUTCOME_CHOICE_VOTING → MAKE_OUTCOME_CHOICE_WINNER
    option.successText set by group vote
  NAVIGATE_WINNER
    playerCoordinates.x++
    → more encounters? loop back to ENCOUNTER RESOLUTION
    → round done, round < 2? loop back to STORY WRITING
    → round >= 2? proceed to epilogue
  │
  ▼
WRITE_EPILOGUES → WRITE_EPILOGUES_WINNER           [SHARE_TEXT]
  Players write about another player's character arc
  │
  ▼
FINALE
```

### Player Assignment Logic

Players are sorted by `joinedAt` timestamp. Work is distributed by offsetting from each player's
index so no one writes about their own content.

| Phase | Assignment |
|---|---|
| `WHAT_HAPPENS_HERE` round 1 | Player gets EncounterLabel authored by player at `index + offset` |
| `WHAT_HAPPENS_HERE` round 2+ | Player gets a Story via `distributeStoriesToPlayer(offset)` |
| `WHAT_CAN_WE_TRY` | Player gets 1–2 stories from offset players |
| `HOW_DOES_THIS_RESOLVE` | Player gets one story; its WHAT_CAN_WE_TRY submissions are selectable subTypes |
| `MAKE_CHOICE_VOTING` | Only players assigned to the current encounter vote |
| `WRITE_EPILOGUES` | Player writes about the character at `index - offset` |

### Encounter Generation

- `SET_ENCOUNTERS_WINNERS`: Submissions ranked by addition count. Top N become `EncounterLabel[]`
  on `AdventureMap`.
- `WHAT_HAPPENS_HERE_WINNER`: Each winning submission becomes a `Story` placed at `(x+i, y)` on
  the `GameBoard`. Players whose submissions didn't win receive pre-canned stories (e.g., "The
  Slime Lord", "A Festival!", etc.) placed at adjacent coordinates.

